We begin by multiplying the product by
$\displaystyle (-1)^{p-1} \equiv 1 \mod{p}$. This gives

$\displaystyle 1^{2} \cdot 3^{2} \cdot 5^{2} \cdot ... \cdot (p-2)^{2} \equiv 
1^{2} \cdot 3^{2} \cdot 5^{2} \cdot ... \cdot (p-2)^{2} \cdot (-1)^{p-1} \mod{p}$

Now, rewrite each square as $\displaystyle a^{2} = a\cdot a$ and for
each value of \emph{a}, distribute a power of -1. Notice that we have
$\displaystyle (p-1)/2$ terms in our product. So we need to take a
factor of $\displaystyle (-1)^{(p-1)/2}$ to accomplish this. This gives

\begin{align*}
1^{2} \cdot &3^{2} \cdot 5^{2} \cdot ... \cdot (p-2)^{2} \cdot (-1)^{p-1}  \\
&\equiv (1)(-1)(3)(-3)(5)(-5)  ...  (p-2)(-(p-2))\cdot (-1)^{(p-1)/2} \mod{p}
\end{align*}

Now for each negative term, we add \emph{p} to get.

\begin{align*}
(1)(-1)&(3)(-3)(5)(-5) ... (p-2)(-(p-2))\cdot (-1)^{(p-1)/2} \\
&\equiv (1)(p-1)(3)(p-3)(5)(p-5)...(p-2)(2) \cdot (-1)^{(p-1)/2} \mod{p}
\end{align*}

After rearranging the right hand side above, we see that

\begin{align*}
(1)(p-1)&(3)(p-3)(5)(p-5)...(p-2)(2) \cdot (-1)^{(p-1)/2}\\
&\equiv (p-1)!\cdot (-1)^{(p-1)/2} \mod{p}
\end{align*}

By Wilson's Theorem and combining the above, we have

\begin{align*}
1^{2} \cdot &3^{2} \cdot 5^{2} \cdot ... \cdot (p-2)^{2} \\
&\equiv (p-1)!\cdot (-1)^{(p-1)/2} \mod{p}\\
&\equiv (-1)\cdot (-1)^{(p-1)/2} \mod{p} \\
&\equiv (-1)^{(p+1)/2} \mod{p}
\end{align*}

and this was what we wanted to show.
